    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/24122\">#24122</a> defines (undirected) multigraphs, as discussed <a href=\"#narrow/channel/144837-PR-reviews/topic/.2324122.20Multigraphs/with/516427611\">in this PR review thread</a> . </p>\n<p>A few notational discussions have come up, which it makes sense to put to a poll.  </p>\n<p>First : multigraphs have vertex and edge types <code>α</code> and <code>β</code>, and two useful objects are predicates currently called <code>Graph.Inc : β → α → Prop</code> and <code>Graph.Inc₂ : β → α → α → Prop</code> - <code>G.Inc e u</code> means that <code>u</code> is one of the ends of the edge <code>e</code> in <code>G</code>, and <code>G.Inc₂ e x y</code> means that <code>x</code> and <code>y</code> are the two ends of the edge <code>e</code> in <code>G</code> (with appropriate nuances for loop edges).  </p>\n<p>Those names are mine, and I like that the names indicate their relationship.  but at <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"306601\">@Kyle Miller</span>  pointed out, the subscript in <code>Inc₂</code> is a little awkward. Some other options for <code>Inc₂</code> are <code>G.Links e x y</code>, <code>G.IsLink e x y</code>, <code>G.IsEdgeFrom e x y</code>, and also versions more suggestive of the picture where the edge goes in the middle such as <code>G.IsLink x e y</code>. </p>\n<p>This is perhaps a little open-ended for a poll, but I'll follow this post with one.</p>",
        "id": 516780430,
        "sender_full_name": "Peter Nelson",
        "timestamp": 1746659514
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Another option might be to just pick a name that looks nice in lemma names, but come up with a unicode notation which gives the right picture.</p>",
        "id": 516780643,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1746659640
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>/poll How should the condition that <code>e</code> is an edge of <code>G</code> from <code>x</code> to <code>y</code> be named?<br>\n<code>G.Inc₂ e x y</code><br>\n<code>G.Link e x y</code><br>\n<code>G.IsLink e x y</code><br>\nSomething of the form <code>_ x e y</code><br>\nA unicode notation, with <code>link</code> or similar in lemma names<br>\nSomething else</p>",
        "id": 516780840,
        "sender_full_name": "Peter Nelson",
        "timestamp": 1746659760
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Making some arguments into a set is yet another option, such as <code>e ∈ G.edgesFrom x y</code>or <code>(x, y) ∈ G.linksOf e</code></p>",
        "id": 516780903,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1746659778
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think that losing the dot notation would be too much to give up there.</p>",
